        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down. | Bromley. | Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Aug<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Madam.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am very much obliged for the Lychnis seed, which shall be sown immediately;<ref target="#foot.f2"/> &amp; I will try, as you have done, next year to fertilise the little ovaria.—</p>
<p>It is odd about the Linum; I have never failed to find the two forms, though they certainly resemble each other closely.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>In Haste, | Dear Madam | Your sincerely obliged | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4258.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from L. E. Becker, 31 July [1863]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Becker enclosed a hermaphrodite plant of the usually dioecious <hi rend="italic">Lychnis diurna</hi> (<hi rend="italic">L. dioica</hi>), bearing a seed capsule, with her <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4258.xml" resp="#mjhawkins" cert="high">letter of 31 July [1863]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Becker reported having a pot of scarlet <hi rend="italic">Linum</hi>, all the seedlings of which had the long-styled flower form (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4258.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from L. E. Becker, 31 July [1863]</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
